            <h2>Choosing Your Study Abroad Destination</h2>
            <p class="lead">One of the biggest decisions you will face as a prospective international student is choosing which country to study in. With options spanning from the UK and Canada to South Korea and Australia, each destination offers unique advantages in terms of education quality, living costs, work opportunities, and post-graduation pathways. At Grant Consulting, we help students navigate this decision every day, and in this guide we share the key factors you should consider.</p>
            <h2>Key Factors to Consider</h2>
            <p>When evaluating countries, it is important to look beyond just university rankings. Consider the total cost of living, including accommodation, food, and transportation. Research whether the country allows part-time work for international students during the semester and full-time during holidays. Check the post-graduation work visa options, as some countries like Canada and Australia offer generous post-study work permits that can lead to permanent residency.</p>
            <p><strong>Questions to ask yourself:</strong></p>
            <ul class="post-list">
              <li>What is my budget for tuition and living expenses?</li>
              <li>Do I want the option to work part-time while studying?</li>
              <li>What language do I want to study in (English, or am I open to other languages)?</li>
              <li>What are the post-graduation career and immigration opportunities?</li>
            </ul>
